---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    /* Architecture-specific layered diagram */
    .layer-stack { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 12px; }
    .layer {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: var(--card);
      position: relative;
    }
    .layer .layer-label {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 10.5px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }
    .layer .layer-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 6px; }
    .layer .layer-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 12px; }
    .layer .layer-chips { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px; }
    .layer-chip {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      padding: 4px 8px;
      background: var(--muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: 4px;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
    }
    .arrow-down {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      color: var(--text-faint);
      font-size: 14px;
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
    }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="01 · Architecture Overview — Sardis Canvas" currentId="architecture">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 01 · System</span>
        <h1>Architecture Overview</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Sardis is a seven-layer stack. An AI agent enters at the top; real money moves at the bottom.
          Every request traverses the same spine: identity, mandate, policy, orchestration, execution,
          settlement, audit. This canvas shows that spine and why each layer exists.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          AI agents can reason, but they cannot be trusted with money. Sardis inserts a verifiable control
          plane between an agent's decision and a bank rail — non-custodial MPC wallets below, natural-language
          spending policies above, an append-only audit trail on the side. Live on Base and Tempo mainnet.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Core principles -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Principles</div>
          <h2>Five commitments the architecture is shaped around.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            These aren't slogans; each one forces a specific structural choice. Change a principle and the stack
            reshapes around it.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Non-custodial first</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Private keys never live in Sardis memory. All signing goes through an MPC provider
              (Turnkey default, Fireblocks/Circle/Lit pluggable). <strong>Why it matters:</strong> an agent
              compromised through prompt injection cannot exfiltrate funds because there is no key to steal.
              A platform breach limits blast radius to metadata, not movement.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Policy before execution</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every transaction passes through <code>PaymentOrchestrator</code> →
              <code>PreExecutionPipeline</code> (policy + KYC/AML + mandate + rate limits + anomaly).
              <strong>Why it matters:</strong> there is no "private fast path" — wallets, mandates, ap2
              routers all funnel through the same gate, so one hardening improves safety everywhere.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Fail-closed by default</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Compliance failure, policy failure, unreachable KYA/FIDES service — all default to deny.
              <strong>Why it matters:</strong> agents run unattended; "when in doubt, allow" is how you
              wake up to a regulator letter. The override flag (<code>SARDIS_AGIT_FAIL_OPEN=true</code>)
              exists for local dev only.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Audit everything, anchor it on-chain</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every decision writes a ledger entry; batches are Merkle-rooted and anchored via
              <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>. <strong>Why it matters:</strong> agent disputes resolve to
              cryptographic evidence, not logs that could have been edited.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Provider abstraction</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every external service — MPC, KYC, AML, card issuer, fiat rail, PSP — sits behind an
              interface in <code>packages/sardis-core</code>. <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Didit
              replaced Persona without touching business logic; Lithic can replace Stripe Issuing when
              funding requirements allow. Swap cost stays low, lock-in stays zero.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Open-core moat</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Framework SDKs, protocol verifiers, reference contracts — open source.
              Policy engine, trust graph, enterprise compliance — proprietary.
              <strong>Why it matters:</strong> distribution goes viral through SDKs; revenue defends
              through the parts regulated entities actually pay for.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Layered view -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">The Spine</div>
          <h2>Seven layers — top to bottom.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Read top-to-bottom for a request's journey; bottom-to-top for a money movement's journey.
            Canvas <a href="/payment-flow">07 · Payment Flow</a> walks one request through every box.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="layer-stack">

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 1 · Agent Surface</div>
            <div class="layer-title">AI framework SDKs + MCP + CLI</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              Where the agent code actually lives. Thin adapters that expose Sardis primitives (pay,
              policy check, wallet balance) as native tools in each framework. Zero crypto concepts leak up.
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-langchain</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-crewai</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-openai-agents</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-agent-sdk</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-adk</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-agentkit</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-mcp-server</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-cli</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">+ 10 more</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ HTTPS / JSON</div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 2 · API Gateway</div>
            <div class="layer-title">FastAPI · 123 routers · auth + rate limit + CSP</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              Composition root: <code>packages/sardis-api/src/sardis_api/main.py</code>. Every router is grouped
              by domain (auth, wallets, payments, policy, checkout, compliance, ops). CSP/HSTS/CORS enforced
              at middleware; principal extraction in <code>require_principal</code>; rate limits Redis-backed.
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">auth / api_keys / me</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">wallets / agents / groups</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">payments / pay / ap2 / mandates</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">checkout / merchant_checkout</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">compliance / kyc_onboarding</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">admin / emergency / kill_switch</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ <code>PaymentOrchestrator.execute()</code></div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 3 · Pre-Execution Pipeline</div>
            <div class="layer-title">Policy + Compliance + Mandate + Limits + Anomaly</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              The single gate. Implements AGIT (Agent Identity and Trust), KYA (Know Your Agent), FIDES
              (trust graph), and the Spending Policy engine. Fail-closed; every deny is audited with
              reason code.
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">spending_policy.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">agit_policy_engine.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">anomaly_detection.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">approval_service.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">rate_limiter</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">erc8183_policy_guard.py</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ approved intent</div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 4 · Protocol Verification</div>
            <div class="layer-title">AP2 · TAP · x402 · A2A mandate chains</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              If the request arrived via a standard protocol (Google/Visa/Mastercard AP2, Visa TAP, x402
              402-Payment-Required, Google A2A), the full mandate chain is verified — Ed25519/ECDSA-P256
              sigs, replay cache, TTL — before the orchestrator will even schedule a transaction.
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-protocol</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">MandateVerifier</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">ReplayCache (Postgres + Redis)</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">MandateArchive</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ signed mandate</div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 5 · Orchestration + Wallet</div>
            <div class="layer-title">ChainExecutor · WalletManager · MPC signing</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              Chooses the rail (Base, Tempo, Ethereum, Polygon, Arbitrum, Optimism), selects the token
              (USDC, EURC, USDT, PYUSD), requests an MPC signature from Turnkey (or Fireblocks/Circle),
              and submits to the appropriate RPC. Dedicated executors for Tempo
              (<code>tempo/executor.py</code>) and EVM chains.
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-chain/executor.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-wallet/manager.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">tempo_keychain.py</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">Circle Paymaster (USDC gas)</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">Pimlico (backup)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ broadcast tx</div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 6 · Settlement</div>
            <div class="layer-title">CCTP v2 · Fiat rails · Stripe Connect</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              Cross-chain USDC via Circle CCTP v2 (unified addresses). Fiat off-ramp via Stripe Connect
              (US), Striga (EU vIBANs + SEPA), Bridge (multi-rail). Settlement is explicit and reconciled —
              not "best effort."
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">CCTP v2 burn/mint</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">merchant_payout</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">striga_vibans</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">bridge (ACH/SEPA/PIX)</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">reconciliation_queue</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="arrow-down">↓ state hashes</div>

          <div class="layer">
            <div class="layer-label">Layer 7 · Audit + Ledger</div>
            <div class="layer-title">Append-only ledger · Merkle anchor · Evidence export</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">
              Every decision — approved, denied, errored — writes a ledger row. Batches are Merkle-rooted
              and anchored on-chain via <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>. Operators and regulators get
              cryptographic evidence, not "trust our logs."
            </div>
            <div class="layer-chips">
              <span class="layer-chip">sardis-ledger</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">policy_decisions</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">evidence_export</span>
              <span class="layer-chip">data_export</span>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Mermaid flow -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Interaction</div>
          <h2>One request, end to end.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            A simplified sequence — what happens when an agent calls <code>sardis.pay(to, amount)</code>.
            Canvas <a href="/payment-flow">07 · Payment Flow</a> expands every box here with real code references.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
sequenceDiagram
    participant A as Agent (LangChain)
    participant S as Sardis SDK
    participant G as API Gateway
    participant P as Pre-Execution Pipeline
    participant V as Protocol Verifier
    participant O as Orchestrator
    participant W as Wallet/MPC
    participant C as Chain (Base/Tempo)
    participant L as Ledger + Anchor

    A->>S: pay(to, amount, reason)
    S->>G: POST /v1/payments (API key auth)
    G->>P: require_principal + orchestrator.execute()
    P->>P: Spending policy ✓
    P->>P: KYC/AML ✓
    P->>P: Mandate delegation ✓
    P->>P: Rate limit ✓
    P->>P: Anomaly score ≥ threshold ✓
    P->>V: verify AP2/TAP mandate chain
    V-->>P: signed ok
    P->>O: approved intent
    O->>W: request MPC signature (Turnkey)
    W-->>O: signed tx
    O->>C: broadcast (Alchemy RPC)
    C-->>O: tx hash + receipt
    O->>L: append ledger_entry + policy_decision
    L->>L: Merkle batch + on-chain anchor
    O-->>G: PaymentResult
    G-->>S: 200 OK
    S-->>A: { tx_hash, status }
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Two planes -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Planes</div>
          <h2>Data plane vs. control plane.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            A common source of confusion: Sardis has two planes. The <strong>data plane</strong> moves money.
            The <strong>control plane</strong> moves opinions <em>about</em> money — policies, approvals,
            trust graph updates, anomaly thresholds. They share a database but not a code path.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Data plane — "do the thing"</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              API gateway → orchestrator → wallet → chain. Synchronous, latency-sensitive (agents are
              watching a response), fail-closed. Owned by <code>sardis-api</code>, <code>sardis-chain</code>,
              <code>sardis-wallet</code>.
            </div>
            <dl class="defs mt-16">
              <dt>Latency budget</dt><dd>~2s p99 end-to-end (excluding chain confirmation)</dd>
              <dt>Blast radius on bug</dt><dd>money moves wrong → fail-closed design contains</dd>
              <dt>Owner test suite</dt><dd><code>tests/integration</code> + on-chain replay</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Control plane — "decide the policy"</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Dashboard + policy manager + approvals + kill switch + trust registry + webhooks +
              live events. Async, eventually consistent, human-in-the-loop friendly.
              Owned by <code>apps/dashboard</code>, <code>sardis-core</code> policy modules,
              event streaming routers.
            </div>
            <dl class="defs mt-16">
              <dt>Latency budget</dt><dd>~5s to UI from event bus</dd>
              <dt>Blast radius on bug</dt><dd>bad policy → caught at next execution (fail-closed)</dd>
              <dt>Owner test suite</dt><dd>Playwright (dashboard) + policy unit tests</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Key files -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Source of Truth</div>
          <h2>Key files if you want to dig in.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Layer</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/config.py</code></td><td>Everything</td><td>The canonical configuration. Every env var, every provider toggle, every chain config. If you want to know what's live, start here.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/orchestrator.py</code></td><td>3 · Gate</td><td><code>PaymentOrchestrator</code> — the single chokepoint through which wallets, mandates, ap2, pay all flow.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/spending_policy.py</code></td><td>3 · Gate</td><td>The policy engine. Natural-language input → structured policy → enforcement at runtime.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-api/src/sardis_api/main.py</code></td><td>2 · Gateway</td><td>FastAPI composition root. Shows all 123 routers wired up with middleware.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-chain/src/sardis_v2_chain/executor.py</code></td><td>5 · Execution</td><td>Chain selection, RPC submission, receipt parsing. Multi-chain orchestration lives here.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-wallet/src/sardis_wallet/manager.py</code></td><td>5 · Execution</td><td>Wallet lifecycle + MPC signing. Where Turnkey/Fireblocks/Circle is abstracted.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-protocol/src/sardis_v2_protocol/ap2.py</code></td><td>4 · Verification</td><td>AP2 mandate-chain verifier — Intent → Cart → Payment signatures.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-ledger</code></td><td>7 · Audit</td><td>Append-only ledger + Merkle batching. Feeds on-chain anchor.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>contracts/src/SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code></td><td>7 · Audit</td><td>On-chain anchor for Merkle-rooted evidence batches.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/dashboard/app/(dashboard)</code></td><td>Control plane</td><td>43 operator pages — policies, approvals, kill switch, live events.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Where it runs -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Deployment Topology</div>
          <h2>Where each piece actually runs.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Surface</th><th>Runtime</th><th>Region</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>API (sardis-api)</td><td>Cloud Run</td><td>us-central1</td><td>Gunicorn + uvicorn inside Docker; 300s timeout; Fluid-compute-equivalent concurrency.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dashboard (apps/dashboard)</td><td>Vercel</td><td>Edge</td><td>Next.js 16 App Router (React 19); fluid compute for RSC; <code>app.sardis.sh</code> + <code>dashboard.sardis.sh</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Landing (apps/landing)</td><td>Vercel</td><td>Edge</td><td>Next.js; <code>sardis.sh</code>; static + incremental for blog/compare pages.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Checkout UI (sardis-checkout-ui)</td><td>Vercel</td><td>Edge</td><td><code>checkout.sardis.sh</code>. Embeddable SDK served from same origin.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Database</td><td>Neon Postgres</td><td>us-east</td><td>Serverless; 107 migrations applied in order; branching for preview envs.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Cache / rate-limit / dedup</td><td>Upstash Redis</td><td>global</td><td>Required in prod (<code>SARDIS_REDIS_URL</code>); rate limiter fail-closed if unreachable.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>MPC signing</td><td>Turnkey API</td><td>Provider</td><td>Organization + sub-org per tenant; keys never leave Turnkey.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chain RPC</td><td>Alchemy</td><td>Provider</td><td>Env-driven (<code>SARDIS_BASE_RPC_URL</code>, etc.); public RPC as fallback.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Event streaming</td><td>SSE + webhook outbox</td><td>Cloud Run</td><td>Per-merchant stream; outbox pattern for webhook at-least-once.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Smart contracts</td><td>Base + Tempo mainnet</td><td>L2</td><td>See canvas 06 for addresses.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Cross-refs -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Go deeper</div>
          <h2>Follow-ups.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/repo-structure">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">02 · System</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Repo Structure</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">The monorepo tree, folder by folder. Start here if you cloned and got lost.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/payment-flow">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">07 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Payment Flow</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">The sequence above, but every box expanded to the actual function it calls.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/policy-engine">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">08 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Policy Engine</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">How natural language becomes a structured policy and how it's enforced.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/security">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">19 · Ops</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Security Model</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">Trust boundaries, fail-closed defaults, threat model.</div>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
</Canvas>